# Who blocks OpenAI, Google AI and Common Crawl?

In total, {{ "{:,.0f}".format(disallow_count) }} of {{ "{:,.0f}".format(site_count) }} news publishers surveyed by the [homepages.news](https://homepages.news) archive have instructed [OpenAI](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OpenAI), [Google AI](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Google_AI) or the non-profit [Common Crawl](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_Crawl) to stop scanning their sites, which is {{ "{:,.1f}".format(disallow_percent) }}% of the sample.

The three organizations systematically crawl the web to gather the data that, among other things, fuels [generative chatbots](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generative_artificial_intelligence) like [OpenAI's ChatGPT](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ChatGPT) and [Google's Bard](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bard_(chatbot)). Publishers can request that their content be excluded by opting out via the [robots.txt](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robots.txt) convention.

The open-source system run by [homepages.news](https://homepages.news/) gathers each news site's robots.txt file twice per day. This page continually updates with the latest results.

